│ The `getConstraintForSolving` method in the `ConstraintInfo` class is responsible for      │
│ converting a comparison predicate and operands into a constraint that can be used for      │
│ reasoning. It handles trivial cases, converts signed predicates to unsigned ones when both │
│ operands are non-negative, and ensures that no new variables are introduced when returning │
│ a constraint.                                                                              │
│                                                                                            │
│ The `isImpliedBy` method in the `ConstraintTy` class checks whether a constraint is        │
│ implied by the current constraint system. It evaluates the condition and its negation to   │
│ determine if the condition is implied, not implied, or inconclusive.                       │
│                                                                                            │
│ The issue likely arises from overly aggressive assumptions in `isImpliedBy` or             │
│ `getConstraintForSolving`, leading to incorrect transformations. Specifically, the         │
│ transformation may incorrectly determine that a condition is implied when it is not,       │
│ resulting in the replacement of the condition with a constant.                             │
│                                                                                            │
│ To address this, I will propose an edit point to add additional checks or constraints to   │
│ ensure that conditions are only replaced when they are conclusively implied. Let me        │
│ finalize the edit points and provide the reasoning.                                        │
