│ Based on the code for `isImpliedBy` and `getConstraintForSolving`, the issue lies in       │
│ overly aggressive assumptions when determining if a condition is implied. Specifically:    │
│                                                                                            │
│ 1. **`isImpliedBy`**: The function may return `true` or `false` even when the evidence is  │
│ inconclusive. This can lead to incorrect transformations, as seen in the bug report.       │
│ 2. **`getConstraintForSolving`**: The function may return constraints that introduce new   │
│ variables, which are not valid for reasoning. This can also lead to incorrect conclusions. │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### Proposed Fix                                                                           │
│                                                                                            │
│ 1. **`isImpliedBy`**:                                                                      │
│    - Add stricter checks to ensure that conditions are only replaced when they are         │
│ conclusively implied.                                                                      │
│    - Modify the logic to return `std::nullopt` when the evidence is inconclusive.          │
│                                                                                            │
│ 2. **`getConstraintForSolving`**:                                                          │
│    - Add a check to ensure that the returned constraint is valid for reasoning.            │
│    - If the constraint introduces new variables or is otherwise invalid, return an empty   │
│ constraint.                                                                                │
│                                                                                            │
│ I will now implement these changes.                                                        │
